VRA Section 2 Analysis-Congressional Districts

DRAFTâ€“Internal Use Only

5/28/2021

Initial Analysis of VRA Section 2 assessment is to check the race/ethnicity of the current district to get a baseline of minority VAP/CVAP from 2010. If the minority population hasnâ€™t decreased, then we need to at least keep the same number of minority opportunity districts as last time.

Steps

  1. Get race/eth summary by congressional district from 2010.
  2. Compare race/eth summary from 2010 to race/eth summary from most recent estimates (2019 ACS) to review population changes.
  3. Determine how many minority opportunity districts you can create where the race/ethnicity share is 50%+.

Step 1: Identify 2010 Minority Opportunity Districts

Which current Congressional Districts had 50% or more of the Citizen Voting Age Population (CVAP) in 2010?

Latinx

  • Of Congressional districts in/around LA County, 40 (SELA-Huntington Park), 35 (Pomona-Orange County), 38 (SELA-Whittier), 29 (SFV), 32 (SGV East) and 34 (Koreatown, East LA) had a Latinx CVAP share exceeding 50% in 2010.

Black

  • Of Congressional districts in/around LA County, none had majority Black CVAP in 2010. Districts 37 (South/Central/West LA), 43 (Inglewood/South Bay) and 44 (Compton/South Bay East) had the highest share in the state (around 28-33% CVAP).

Asian

  • Of Congressional districts in/around LA County, none had majority Asian CVAP in 2010. District 27 (Pasadena) had the highest share in the county (33%), followed by District 39 (SGV-Orange County).

Step 2: Identify Population Changes from 2011

How has the Citizen Voting Age Population Changed?

Latinx CVAP Changes

  • In the districts where the Latinx CVAP share exceeded 50% in 2010, the Latinx CVAP share has increased substantially over the past ten years (with the exception of District 34, which remained about the same).

  • Districts 35 (Pomona-Orange County) and 44 (Compton-South Bay) have had about a 10 percentage point increase in Latinx CVAP.

Black CVAP Changes

  • Congressional districts in and around LA County have had an overall decrease or steady maintenance in Black CVAP.

  • There are a few districts with small increases in Black CVAP (e.g.Â District 8 (San Bernardino County), 23 (Lancaster-Kern County), 30 (SFV-Canoga Park-Sherman Oaks)), but are not close to having majority of the total CVAP.

Asian CVAP Changes

  • Congressional districts in and around LA County have had an overall increase or steady maintenance in Asian CVAP.

  • Districts 27 (Pasadena) and 39 (SGV-Orange County) have had substantial Asian CVAP increases, but are not close to having the majority.

Summary:

  • We will have at least 7 Latinx opportunity districts, as there were 7 in 2010 and there were no significant population decreases. It is likely weâ€™ll have more than 7, possibly a minimum of 8 Latinx opportunity districts. .

  • While we could potentially draw a Black opportunity district, we should consult with partners on how desirable that may be as it may decrease Black voting power via packing.

  • We could potentially draw an Asian opportunity district around Pasadena-SGV-around the Orange County border. It is still to be seen if that is feasible, given the data, and desirable, given partner input.

Step 3: Given the current CVAP, how many minority opportunity districts can be created?

What is the ideal total population per district?

  • US Census Bureau apportionment population is 39,576,757, and 52 districts have been allocated to California.

  • Dividing the state population by 52 districts means the ideal district population is 761,091.
